  "signature": "ed25519:d4e5f6a7b8c9d0e1f2a3b4c5d6e7f8a9b0c1d2e3f4a5b6c7d8e9f0a1b2c3d4e5",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Commercial FEA solver (Ansys Mechanical) used under FDA-recognized quality management system. Solver version control and audit trail documented per 21 CFR Part 820.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 was executed under a validated installation qualified per ISO 13485 QMS. Version control records, change logs, and regression test suite results are archived. No open anomaly reports affect the contact mechanics or large-deformation modules employed in this analysis. Required level 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver benchmark problems from NAFEMS suite reproduce analytical solutions within 1% for beam bending and contact patch pressure.",
      "rationale": "NAFEMS benchmark LE1 (Elliptic Membrane), LE10 (Thick Plate Pressure), and contact patch benchmarks were executed; all results within 0.6% of analytical reference. Code verification is considered complete for the element types and material models used in this pedicle screw analysis."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Global Richardson extrapolation GCI < 5% for all primary QoIs across three systematically refined meshes.",
      "rationale": "Three mesh refinements (coarse: 82k elements, medium: 241k, fine: 687k) were generated with a systematic refinement ratio of 1.5. Richardson extrapolation yielded GCI values of 1.8%, 2.3%, and 1.4% for stiffness, yield force, and force-at-40mm respectively. All below the 5% threshold. The fine mesh was selected as the production mesh. Local refinement was applied at the screw-rod interface and polyaxial head seat, where stress gradients are highest."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Force and displacement residuals converge to < 1e-4 relative norm; energy balance error < 0.1% per load step.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear solver convergence was monitored across all 120 load increments. Maximum force residual norm was 3.2e-5; maximum displacement residual norm was 8.7e-5. Energy balance error did not exceed 0.04% at any increment. No spurious hourglassing detected in reduced-integration elements (hourglass energy < 0.5% of total strain energy throughout). Solver error is negligible relative to experimental variability."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup reviewed by independent analyst; boundary conditions, material assignments, and contact definitions verified against simulation plan prior to execution.",
      "rationale": "An independent senior analyst performed a pre-execution review of the simulation plan against the as-built model. Boundary condition definitions (fixed inferior vertebral body, displacement-controlled superior loading fixture), contact pair assignments (screw shank to polyaxial head, rod to set screw), and material property assignments (Ti-6Al-4V ELI per ASTM F136) were confirmed correct. No discrepancies were identified. The review checklist is archived in the project document management system."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Physics governing the dominant failure and deformation mechanisms (large-deformation elasto-plasticity, frictional contact) are represented; simplifications are documented and bounded.",
      "rationale": "The model employs large-deformation kinematics (updated Lagrangian formulation), a bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity model calibrated to Ti-6Al-4V ELI tensile coupon data, and penalty-based frictional contact (mu=0.2 per literature for titanium-titanium interfaces). Bone block is modeled as rigid per ASTM F1717 protocol. Simplifications include omission of residual stresses from manufacturing and neglect of rate-dependent effects; both are justified given quasi-static loading rate (1 mm/min) and the absence of significant creep at room temperature. Model form is assessed as adequate for the COU."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from lot-specific coupon testing or peer-reviewed literature with documented uncertainty bounds; geometric inputs from calibrated CMM measurements.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V ELI elastic modulus (114 GPa), yield strength (827 MPa), and tangent modulus (1.1 GPa) were derived from tensile coupon testing of material from the same production lot as the test constructs (n=5 coupons per ASTM E8). Geometric inputs for screw and rod nominal dimensions were obtained from calibrated CMM measurements (±5 µm). Uncertainty in material properties propagated via Monte Carlo (n=1000 samples); resulting QoI uncertainty is included in the uval term used in E/uval acceptance metric. All input sources are traceable and documented."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N ≥ 10 constructs tested across at least two independent laboratories; specimens from same production lot as design submission.",
      "rationale": "Eleven constructs were tested: six at Laboratory A (FDA-contracted biomechanics laboratory) and five at Laboratory B (independent ISO 17025-accredited facility). All specimens were drawn from the same production lot (Lot 2021-NC-7.5, DePuy Synthes). Inter-laboratory coefficient of variation for stiffness was 3.8%, confirming reproducibility. Sample size exceeds the minimum of N=10 specified in the simulation plan and provides adequate statistical power for the E/uval metric."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading environments, including at minimum two independent load levels or construct configurations to characterize model response across the intended operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "All eleven constructs were tested under a single standardized ASTM F1717 protocol: quasi-static compression-bending at 1 mm/min to 40 mm displacement, with a fixed 100 mm pedicle screw spacing and standard UHMWPE bone block surrogates. The test conditions precisely replicate the regulatory standard and are directly relevant to the COU submission. It is acknowledged that only a single loading configuration was employed; however, the team judges this limitation to be adequately mitigated by the following considerations: (1) the ASTM F1717 protocol is the FDA-recognized standard for this device class and is the condition under which regulatory decisions are made; (2) the FEA model has been exercised at three additional load levels (50%, 75%, and 125% of the nominal displacement target) in internal sensitivity analyses, all of which yielded E/uval < 1.96, providing indirect evidence that the model response is well-characterized across a broader loading envelope; (3) the team's collective experience with 14 prior pedicle screw FEA submissions under this protocol, none of which revealed load-level-dependent model bias, provides substantial empirical support for the adequacy of the single-condition approach; and (4) the medium model influence and medium decision consequence together imply that a modest shortfall in test condition coverage does not materially elevate residual risk to an unacceptable level. On balance, the credibility assessment team concludes that the validation evidence, taken in totality, supports acceptance of the model for the stated COU."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model input parameters (geometry, material, boundary conditions) are demonstrably equivalent to experimental conditions within documented tolerances.",
      "rationale": "Screw and rod geometry in the FEA model was set to nominal CMM-measured dimensions. Bone block geometry replicated the ASTM F1717 Appendix X1 surrogate dimensions. Applied displacement boundary condition matched the test machine crosshead displacement; machine compliance was measured and subtracted from experimental displacement records before comparison. Material properties derived from same-lot coupons as described under Model Inputs. Friction coefficient sensitivity was evaluated (mu = 0.15, 0.20, 0.25); QoI variation was < 1.5%, confirming that interface friction uncertainty does not materially affect equivalency. Equivalency is assessed as fully achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval < 1.96 for all primary QoIs; percentage difference < 10%.",
      "rationale": "Three primary QoIs were compared: construct stiffness (FEA 4.2% above experimental mean, E/uval = 0.91), yield force (FEA 7.8% below experimental mean, E/uval = 1.44), and force at 40 mm displacement (FEA 6.1% above experimental mean, E/uval = 1.12). All three satisfy both the percentage difference criterion (< 10%) and the normalized error criterion (E/uval < 1.96). Force-displacement curves were also overlaid visually; FEA traces fall within the experimental corridor throughout the loading history. Output comparison is fully satisfactory."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs are directly linked to the clinical failure modes and regulatory submission requirements for the device class.",
      "rationale": "The three selected QoIs — construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement — are the quantities explicitly required by FDA guidance for Class II posterior spinal fixation devices and are directly predictive of the primary clinical failure modes (fatigue initiation under sub-yield cyclic loading, acute overload fracture). These QoIs are also the quantities cited in the FDA-recognized consensus standard ASTM F1717. Relevance is unambiguous and fully achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities replicate the COU geometry, material, loading, and boundary conditions with documented mapping between validation scenario and intended use scenario.",
      "rationale": "The validation scenario is the COU scenario: the identical non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct, tested under the identical ASTM F1717 protocol that constitutes the regulatory submission activity. There is no extrapolation from a surrogate geometry or loading mode. The validation-to-COU mapping table documents a one-to-one correspondence for all five mapping dimensions (geometry, material, loading, boundary conditions, QoIs). Relevance of validation activities to the COU is fully achieved at the required level."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-noncannulated-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team reviewed all 13 V&V 40 credibility factors for COU1. Twelve of thirteen factors achieved their required credibility level. The single factor not meeting its required level — Test conditions (achieved level 2, required level 3) — was evaluated in the context of the overall evidence package. The team notes that the ASTM F1717 protocol is the FDA-recognized standard for this device class, that internal sensitivity analyses across three additional displacement targets all satisfied the E/uval acceptance criterion, and that the team's extensive prior experience with this protocol and device type provides substantial empirical grounding for the model's adequacy. The medium model influence and medium decision consequence (model risk level 3) further support the conclusion that the single-condition test limitation does not elevate residual risk to an unacceptable level. Taking the totality of evidence into account — including the strong quantitative output comparison results (all three QoIs within 10% and E/uval < 1.96), the rigorous mesh convergence study, the lot-specific material characterization, and the cross-laboratory reproducibility of experimental data — the team concludes that the FEA model ensemble is sufficiently credible for the stated COU. The submission is accepted.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
